except: As Michal was not divorced, but violently separated from David,
he had a legal right to demand her, and was justified in receiving her
again. It is probable, also, that her marriage with Phaltiel was a force
upon her inclinations; and whatever affections he might have for her, it
was highly criminal for him to take another man's wife. David required
Michal probably both out of affection for her, and to strengthen his
interest, by asserting his affinity with the house of Saul.

